participating-org.narrative:
Saferworld (SW) was established in 1989 and formerly worked as a campaign organisation on nuclear proliferation, most notably working on the Freeze campaign, a campaign set up to respond to new challenges of the post-Cold War scenario. In 1994, Saferworld published ‘The True Cost of Conflict,’ which provided new insights into the debate on global security, and studied the costs of 7 differentconflicts on health, education, civil and political rights, trade, power supply and transportation amongst others. In 1997 the Hornof Africa project- examining the impact of EU policies on the Horn of Africa – was Saferworld’s first project to involve significant ‘on the ground’ research.

Today Saferworld is an independent international not-for-profit organisation working to prevent and reduce violent conflict, promote co-operative approaches to security-building and build safer lives. Since 1989, the organisation has developed considerably with programmes in nearly 20 countries and territories across Eastern Europe and Central Asia, South Asia, Middle East and North Africa, Kenya and the Horn of Africa, and the Great Lakes regions, where it contributes to lasting change. It employs over a 100 members of staff located at our headquarters in London as well as in Bishkek, Brussels, Dhaka, Juba, Kampala, Kathmandu, Nairobi, Pristine, Sana’a, Tbilisi, Vienna and Washington. Saferworld’s annual income has grown from £3,000,000 in 2007/8 to over £9,000,000 in 2012/13.

SW also maintains a strong thematic focus in its work, prioritising four central issue areas:
I. Access to security and justice;
II. The control of conventional weapons;
III. The relationship between aid and conflict;
IV. The relationship between governance and peacebuilding.

Saferworld works with local people affected by conflict to improve their safety and sense of security, and conducts wider research and analysis. It uses this evidence and learning to improve local, national and international policies and practices that can help build lasting peace. Its priority is people – guided by the belief that everyone should be able to lead peaceful, fulfilling lives, free from insecurity and violent conflict.

Understanding and acting on the relationships between gender, peace and security is a cross-cutting set of issues tackled by Saferworld’s interventions across the globe. Examples include integrating gender issues in new community security projects in Bangladesh, South Sudan, and Yemen – initiatives designed to empower local people to find solutions to their own safety and security concerns. Saferworld also started a new project across the Middle East to strengthen women’s voices and ensure that the many women who played a part in the ‘Arab Spring’ have a greater say in decision-making. And at a policy level, Saferworld provides analysis and technical advice to ensure that e.g. preventing sexual violence against women, girls, and boys in conflict was included in the G8 declaration on the issue, and highlighted the impact of genderin securityand justice reform processes.
